english:
  title: In Response to Secretary Pae's Poem on Mountain Camellia Flowers
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I remember wandering east of Penglai in days long past,
    when mountain camellia bloomed and sea-clouds turned red.
    Coral branches bent like embroidered palace screens—
    and there, in winter's coldest depths, I sat enveloped in spring wind.

    Yet years have rushed by in sudden succession,
    and everywhere I turn, only banners of war appear.
    The realm of immortals and the world of men have grown estranged,
    no word can pass between them anymore.
    Those flowers open and fall, drift and scatter on the river wind.

    Now my gaze grows dazzled by the profusion of peach blossoms,
    and my poetry has come to resemble a Shandong farmer's speech.
    Suddenly we meet again south of Buncheon's walls—
    tell me, was what I saw before empty, or was it real?

    Before the flowers I pour wine and bid my Ssangsong soul to linger.
    So I ask: who is the true master of this moment?
  footnotes:
    - 'Penglai (蓬萊): A legendary island of immortals in Chinese mythology, representing a lost paradise.'
    - The poem is written in response to a work by Secretary Pae (裴祕書), following the tradition of 차운 (response poetry) where poets compose using the same rhyme scheme.
    - 'Ssangsong (雙松): Likely a reference to the author''s pen name or spiritual identity, meaning ''twin pines.'''
    - The shift from mountain camellia to peach blossoms mirrors the poet's journey from an idealized past to a troubled present, with war's turmoil intruding upon nature's cycle.
